<DOC><DOCNO> AP880311-0037 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0356EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-IllinoisPoll     03-11 0236</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Illinois Poll,200</SECOND><HEAD>Bush Holds Wide Lead Over Dole In Illinois, Poll Suggests</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Vice President George Bush leads Senate GOPleader Bob Dole by a wide margin among Republicans likely to votein Illinois' presidential primary, according to survey resultspublished today.   The Washington Post-ABC News telephone poll conducted Wednesday,six days before the primary election, showed Bush with the supportof 58 percent of 395 likely Republican voters, while Dole, ofKansas, was backed by 31 percent.   Former television evangelist Pat Robertson was the choice of 6percent while Rep. Jack Kemp of New York, who dropped out of therace on Thursday, had 4 percent, according to the survey, which waspublished in today's editions of the Post.   In the Democratic race, native sons Sen. Paul Simon of Illinoisand civil rights leader Jesse Jackson of Chicago led with 38percent and 33 percent, respectively, among 402 likely Democraticvoters. The difference between the two was within the poll's marginof error.   Massachussets Gov. Michael Dukakis trailed with 16 percent andRep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri had 6 percent. Former Sen. GaryHart of Colorado, who was expected to withdraw from the contesttoday, was picked by 3 percent of the respondents and Sen. AlbertGore of Tennessee was chosen by 2 percent.   The newspaper said the survey had a margin of error of plus orminus eight percentage points.</TEXT></DOC>